---
Midgaard's charter system — registry primacy, witnessed transactions, public tribunal — is recognizably derived from Measure Script's dual-function inscription tradition. The First Stone Accord's practice of documenting all transactions at watched squares is a direct practical echo of Keeper survey stations. Midgaard's Charter Sovereignty office holds Keeper-era survey documents in its deep archive as "pre-charter precedent" — legally non-binding but historically authoritative for questions about which institutions have governed specific territories longest. This archive is the basis for several rulings favoring historical Keeper governance over more recent competing claims. The Reckoning faction notes the selective application: Keeper precedent is cited when it supports Midgaard's claims and not cited when it would support non-human corridor communities' claims.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has independently traced its notation system back to the Keepers' Littoral Branch through comparative document analysis. The reconstruction project was motivated by the discovery that Mafdet's Ledger Houses use a similar notation — the shared origin in Littoral Branch script was confirmed when the Jade Clerks found maritime trade documents using the same volumetric-legal glyph combinations. The Jade Magistracy's reconstruction places their institutional lineage in the maritime Keeper tradition rather than the inland tradition Midgaard claims — a significant political assertion, since it means Kowloon's governance system is not derivative of Midgaard's charter tradition but a parallel descendant of the same pre-charter source. The Neon Covenant's founding inscription was made in phosphorescent squid dye partly because Littoral Branch tradition required maritime-origin materials for founding documents.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's founding archivists documented Keeper-era survey records during foundation excavations at the Evermeet ruins site. The excavation records show that Evermeet had been a Keeper survey station before it became a fortified city — the watch-square layout of Evermeet's ruins matches Keeper administrative compound geometry. Kiess's three-power governance structure was partly modeled on the Keeper survey station's three functional divisions: measurement and record, route enforcement, and dispute arbitration. Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine addresses a failure that the Keeper system contained in potential: Measure Script's dual-function inscription meant that describing a person's status and legally fixing that status were the same act. The potential for institutional abuse was structural.

flags RAKUEN
---
Rakuen's Garden Ledger system uses accounting formats tracing to Keeper inland-branch survey notation through Midgaard's standardized ledger conventions. The accounting conversion Rakuen performed after the Southmark Petition's refusal — adopting Midgaard ledger standards — moved Rakuen's accounting further from the Keeper survey format and closer to Midgaard's charter-derived system. Rakuen's Compact Purist faction views this conversion as an institutional concession that yielded nothing. The Keeper tradition is referenced in Rakuen political discourse primarily through the Reed Law connection: the Water Court's Burn Ledger emergency reallocation framework preserves Keeper survey law's most practically important feature — the principle that described circumstances create legal obligations. Rakuen's constitutional scholars have proposed that a Keeper-tradition annexation argument — based on historical survey maps showing Rakuen's territory as part of the integrated road network — would be more persuasive than the charter-sovereignty argument Midgaard used to refuse the Iron Compact Appeal.

flags MAFDET
---
Mafdet's Ledger Houses are the living institutional descendants of the Keepers' Littoral Branch. The maritime legal notation Mafdet uses for cargo manifests, oath attestations, and harbor tariff records is a direct descendant of Littoral Branch Measure Script. This institutional lineage gives Mafdet a governance legitimacy claim neither derivative of Midgaard's charter tradition nor in competition with it: the Littoral Branch and the inland branch are parallel descendants of the same Keeper system. Mafdet's concern about Kowloon's Littoral Branch reconstruction project is that successful reconstruction would give Kowloon institutional standing in the maritime legal tradition — potentially creating a competing center of Littoral Branch authority. The Saltglass Reach Wardens' cairn tablet library contains Littoral Branch source documents that Mafdet's Ledger Houses have already accessed; they have not disclosed what those documents contain.

flags MIDGAARD KETHARI
---
Kethari water-memory predates and exceeds any Keeper survey record of the Saltglass Reach's subsurface water systems. Keeper survey crews formally documented Kethari as "knowledgeable about subsurface water systems" but failed to recognize that Kethari water-memory exceeded and predated any Keeper measurement. The Aquifer Covenant governing Deepwell Confluence water-source claims was administered by Kethari communities before the Keepers arrived; Keeper survey law overlaid the Aquifer Covenant without replacing it, creating a dual-system arrangement the Keepers documented without understanding its significance. When the Salt Ledger Kingdoms converted Keeper survey law into hereditary authority, the Aquifer Covenant survived intact underneath — Kethari water-memory transmission is oral and multi-generational, not dependent on the administrative infrastructure the kingdoms took over. Modern Kethari alarm regarding any institution that attempts to reduce water-memory to registry documentation traces to the Keeper period: the Keepers documented Kethari knowledge without incorporating Kethari governance, which created the template for all subsequent institutional engagements with Kethari communities.

