---
Rivennid communities maintained custodial networks across the Keeper road system, supplying waystation infrastructure and keeping information flowing between survey stations. The Keeper survey records document Rivennid custodial presence at junction points throughout the network without classifying it as governance — the same non-institutional documentation applied to all non-human corridor communities. Rivennid cross-system knowledge — understanding how different parts of the Keeper network connected, what each node required, and how information traveled — was more comprehensive than any single Keeper survey station's records. When the Salt Ledger Kingdoms replaced Keeper governance, Rivennid custodial networks continued without interruption. The continuity of Rivennid custodial practice across governance transitions is the feature Rivennid elders cite when explaining why they do not orient their institutional practice around any single city's governance tradition: they have outlasted several already.
